  <static seed="79" source="Contrib/PCC/BasicMath/FractionsCalculation/AddThreeFractions40.pg">
    <statement><p>Add: <m>\displaystyle{ {{\frac{9}{10}}} + {{\frac{7}{9}}} + {{\frac{3}{5}}} }</m></p>
<p><fillin characters="11" name="AnSwEr0001"/></p>
</statement>
    <answer>
      <p>
        <m>2{\textstyle\frac{5}{18}}</m>
      </p>
    </answer>
    <solution><p>To add fractions with different denominators, we need to find the common denominator first. One way is to list the multiples of the largest denominator, until all <m>3</m> denominators divide into the multiple.</p>
<p>The largest denominator is <m>10</m>. We list its first few multiples:</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{ 10, 20, 30, 40, 50, 60, 70, 80, 90 }</m></p>
<p>Note that all denominators, <m>10, 9 \text{ and } 5</m> each divide into <m>90</m>.</p>
<p>The full computation is:</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{\begin{aligned}
   \frac{9}{10} + \frac{7}{9} + \frac{3}{5}
      \amp = \frac{9 \cdot 9}{10 \cdot 9} + \frac{7 \cdot 10}{9 \cdot 10} + \frac{3 \cdot 18}{5 \cdot 18} \\
      \amp = \frac{81}{90} + \frac{70}{90} + \frac{54}{90} \\
      \amp = \frac{81+70+54}{90} \\
      \amp = \frac{205}{90} \\
      \amp = \frac{41}{18} \\
        \amp = {2{\textstyle\frac{5}{18}}}
\end{aligned}
    }</m></p>
<p>Don<rsq/>t forget to reduce the fraction <m>\frac{205}{90}</m> by dividing <m>5</m> into both the numerator and the denominator.</p>
</solution>
